    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="538"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d538">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.00/1008.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Minister <persName type="to">Blanchard</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 31, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your October 30. When <hi rend="italic">Kansas</hi> arrives make similar
                    dispositions for protection of life and property in Gonaives and Saint March
                    that you have for Port au Prince.</p>
                <p>When de facto government is established, Department contemplates conversations
                    looking toward customs convention and a free election under supervision of
                    United States commissioners.</p>
                <p>Continue to keep Department fully advised and include your recommendations,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
